    <segment id="1" parent="21" relname="antithesis">We can go on and on quoting the dictionary for the true meaning of intuitiveness.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="14" relname="circumstance"> 
However, when it comes to software and web interface,</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="21" relname="span">
it is just another catchy term that makes the product more attractive to those who dont know much about software/Web interfaces. </segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="14" relname="elaboration">
Add the warranty, and it would probably cost more. </segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="11" relname="disjunction">
The term intuitiveness shouldnt be use to describe 
how easy it may be to learn a new software or website interface.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="11" relname="disjunction"> 
Nor should it be used to sell more products. </segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="7" relname="preparation">

Take for example my parents, 
who are not technically inclined. </segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="8" relname="span">
If they are using a product that seems easy to them, </segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="15" relname="contrast">
to me it could be quite the opposite. </segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="18" relname="contrast">
On the other hand, if I am working with a product that seems easy to me, </segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="18" relname="contrast">
it may seem difficult to them. </segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="19" relname="summary">
I believe that it is all relative to what the user feels about the product at the time it is being used.</segment>
